ut 1270–Deceased","1270–Female":"1270–Deceased","1263–1320":"1263–1320","1295–Male":"1295–Deceased","1300–Female":"1300–Deceased","1303–Male":"1303–Deceased","1244–Male":"1244–Deceased","about 1270":"about 1270","1263":"1263","1295":"1295","1382":"1382","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1303":"1303","1300":"1300","about 1303":"about 1303","1453":"1453","1244":"1244","1320":"1320","about 1300":"about 1300","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Lancaster, England":"Lancaster, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Farnworth, Lancashire, England":"Farnworth, Lancashire, England","Farneworth, Lancashire, England":"Farnworth, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Bowden","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of several places called Bowden or Bowdon. Bowden in Devon and Derbyshire and Bowdon in Cheshire are named with Old English <i>boga</i> ‘bow’ + <i>dūn</i> ‘hill’, i.e. ‘hill shaped like a bow’; one in Leicestershire (<i>Bugedone</i> in Domesday Book) comes, according to Ekwall, from the Old English personal name <i>Būga</i> (masculine) or <i>Bucge</i> (feminine) + <i>dūn</i>. There are also Scottish places of this name, but there are comparatively few bearers of the surname Bowden north of the border. In England, the surname is found most frequently in Lancashire and in the West Country. In Devon and Cornwall there has been some confusion with the Norman personal name   Baldwin  .","English: topographic name for someone who lived at the top of a hill, from Middle English <i>buve dun</i> ‘above the hill’ (Old English <i>būfan dūne</i>, as in the placename Bowden, Wiltshire).","Scottish: habitational name from Bowden in Roxburghshire, named from Old English <i>bōthl</i> ‘dwelling-house’ + Old English <i>denu</i> ‘valley’."],"variants":[{"name":"Baldwin","meanings":["English and North German: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>bald</i> ‘bold, brave’ + <i>wine</i> ‘friend’, which was extremely popular among the Normans and in Flanders in the early Middle Ages. It was the personal name of the Crusader who in 1100 became the first Christian king of Jerusalem, and of four more Crusader kings of Jerusalem. It was also borne by Baldwin, Count of Flanders (1172–1205), leader of the Fourth Crusade, who became first Latin Emperor of Constantinople (1204). In North America, this surname has absorbed Dutch forms such as <b>Boudewijn</b>.","Irish: surname adopted in Donegal by bearers of the Gaelic surname <b>Ó Maolagáin</b> (see   Milligan  ), due to association of Gaelic <i>maol</i> ‘bald, hairless’ with English <i>bald</i>.","History: A John Baldwin from Buckinghamshire, England, arrived in the US in 1638 and settled in Milford, CT."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":20,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705191,"age":45,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705192,"age":58,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705193,"age":67,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705195,"age":112,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Agnes de Bowden was born about 1270, in Lancashire, England as the daughter of Thomas de Bowden. She married Henry de Hulton in 1295, in Lancaster, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 2 daughters."},"et":{"about 1270–":"umbes 1270–Surnud","1270–Female":"1270–Surnud","1263–1320":"1263–1320","1295–Male":"1295–Surnud","1300–Female":"1300–Surnud","1303–Male":"1303–Surnud","1244–Male":"1244–Surnud","about 1270":"umbes 1270","1263":"1263","1295":"1295","1382":"1382","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1303":"1303","1300":"1300","about 1303":"umbes 1303","1453":"1453","1244":"1244","1320":"1320","about 1300":"umbes 1300","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Lancaster, England":"Lancaster, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Farnworth, Lancashire, England":"Farnworth, Lancashire, England","Farneworth, Lancashire, England":"Farnworth, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England"},"fi":{"about 1270–":"noin 1270–Kuollut","1270–Female":"1270–Kuollut","1263–1320":"1263–1320","1295–Male":"1295–Kuollut","1300–Female":"1300–Kuollut","1303–Male":"1303–Kuollut","1244–Male":"1244–Kuollut","about 1270":"noin 1270","1263":"1263","1295":"1295","1382":"1382","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1303":"1303","1300":"1300","about 1303":"noin 1303","1453":"1453","1244":"1244","1320":"1320","about 1300":"noin 1300","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Lancaster, England":"Lancaster, Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Farnworth, Lancashire, England":"Farnworth, Lancashire, England","Farneworth, Lancashire, England":"Farnworth, Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England"},"fr":{"about 1270–":"environ 1270–Décédée","1270–Female":"1270–Décédée","1263–1320